\begin{abstract}

We ask a question that clinical AI research has largely
sidestepped: not whether a frontier LLM achieves high diagnostic
accuracy on average, but whether its actions are physically safe when
it is wrong and confident. Drawing on the physical AI safety
paradigm---where agents are evaluated not by what they say but by
what they \emph{do} in the world---we introduce the
\textbf{Med-Guard Evaluation Framework}, which places GPT-5 in
simulated multi-turn clinical encounters and measures safety through a
novel suite of action-level physical harm metrics. Evaluating on 50
USMLE-style cases, we find that GPT-5 achieves 62\% diagnostic
accuracy but is severely miscalibrated ($\text{ECE}=0.246$): at
confidence 0.85, covering the majority of cases, actual accuracy is
only 52\%. A rule-based safety guardrail reduces expected physical
harm by 13\%, yet catches 0\% of dangerous actions on incorrect
diagnoses. The system also exhibits systematic diagnostic
over-ordering, requesting a mean of 5.54 tests per case while only
28\% exist in the clinical record. These findings provide specific,
quantified evidence that current frontier LLMs are not yet safe for
autonomous clinical deployment, and that confidence-threshold
guardrails are structurally insufficient for the failure modes that
matter most.
\end{abstract}

