\section{Introduction}

Physical AI safety is concerned with agents whose decisions carry
irreversible physical consequences. A robot arm that misidentifies an
object applies the wrong force. An autonomous vehicle that misreads a
sign injures a pedestrian. A clinical AI system that misdiagnoses a
patient and recommends the wrong treatment harms that
patient~\cite{balogh2015improving}. All three are physically situated
agents operating under uncertainty in high-stakes environments. Yet
the safety tools developed rigorously for the first two---runtime
verification, safety shields, uncertainty
quantification~\cite{alshiekh2018safe,angelopoulos2021conformal}---have
rarely been applied to the third with the same empirical discipline.

This gap is no longer academic. LLMs capable of multi-turn medical
reasoning are being actively evaluated for clinical
deployment~\cite{wang2025survey}. When such a system transitions from
prototype to operational tool, it becomes a physically situated agent
whose outputs cause physical actions and whose errors carry
physiological consequences. Evaluating it purely on diagnostic
accuracy is, by the standards of physical AI safety research,
insufficient.

Current clinical AI evaluation does not meet this standard. Static
benchmarks measure recall of medical knowledge but cannot reveal
whether a model acts prematurely, whether its confidence tracks its
uncertainty, or whether safety mechanisms can intercept dangerous
decisions when the model is confidently wrong~\cite{jin2020medqa}.
No prior work has subjected a frontier proprietary model to
systematic, repeated \emph{action-level} safety evaluation with
physical harm as the primary metric.

Our prior work, Med-Guard~\cite{jain2024medguard}, built a
multi-agent clinical system with dedicated safety agents and a
self-correcting prescription loop, demonstrating improved diagnostic
accuracy and prescription safety over baselines. In this paper, we
repurpose Med-Guard as an evaluation framework---the \emph{Med-Guard
Evaluation Framework}---and ask a harder question: are GPT-5's
actions safe enough for autonomous deployment, and where exactly do
its safety mechanisms fail?

The findings are specific. GPT-5 is severely miscalibrated
($\text{ECE}=0.246$), with 52\% accuracy in its most common
confidence band. It exhibits diagnostic over-ordering (5.54 tests
requested per case, 28\% found). Most critically, the safety guardrail
catches 0\% of dangerous actions on incorrect diagnoses---not because
the design is poor, but because high-confidence wrong decisions are
invisible to threshold logic. These are the failure modes that must
be addressed before autonomous clinical deployment is safe.

\textbf{Contributions:} (1)~The Med-Guard Evaluation Framework,
extending our prior system~\cite{jain2024medguard} with an LLM
patient simulator, dynamic EMR injection, and action-level physical
harm metrics. (2)~The first systematic action-level safety evaluation
of GPT-5 in interactive clinical diagnosis. (3)~A failure mode
taxonomy identifying precisely where safety interventions succeed or
fail. (4)~Evidence that confidence-threshold guardrails are
structurally inadequate for miscalibrated clinical agents.

