\section{Related Work}

\textbf{Physical AI safety.}
Runtime verification and safety shielding intercept agent actions
against formal specifications and block unsafe commands before they
reach the physical system~\cite{alshiekh2018safe}. Uncertainty
quantification ensures agents recognise the limits of their competence
before acting~\cite{angelopoulos2021conformal}. Our guardrail is
architecturally a safety shield. Our central finding---that
confidence-threshold shields fail when the agent is confidently
wrong---has implications for any physically situated system whose
internal confidence signals do not track epistemic uncertainty.

\textbf{LLM-based clinical agents.}
AgentClinic~\cite{schmidgall2025agentclinic} introduced an
interactive benchmark showing structured agent workflows improve
diagnosis over single-model baselines. MDAgents~\cite{kim2024mdagents}
and MEDDxAgent~\cite{rose2025meddxagent} demonstrated adaptive
multi-agent collaboration for differential diagnosis. Our prior
Med-Guard system~\cite{jain2024medguard} introduced dedicated Test
Safety and Prescription Safety agents. The present paper extends that
architecture into an evaluation framework, shifting focus from
accuracy to action-level safety.

\textbf{Safety evaluation of clinical AI.}
MedSafetyBench~\cite{han2024medsafety} and red-teaming
approaches~\cite{balazadeh2025redteam} evaluate output-level safety:
whether LLMs refuse harmful text. MedSentry~\cite{chen2025medsentry}
taxonomises failure modes in multi-agent medical systems. Our safety
concept is distinct: a model that confidently misdiagnoses a patient
and recommends the wrong drug produces no harmful text, would pass
every existing safety benchmark, and would harm the patient.

\textbf{Confidence calibration.}
Guo et al.~\cite{guo2017calibration} showed modern neural networks
are systematically overconfident and proposed temperature scaling as
a post-hoc remedy. Kadavath et al.~\cite{kadavath2022know} found
LLMs degrade in calibration on near-boundary reasoning tasks. Our
work provides the first calibration measurement of GPT-5 in
multi-turn clinical reasoning ($\text{ECE}=0.246$), substantially
above the $<$0.05 threshold appropriate for safety-critical
deployment.

