\section{The Med-Guard Evaluation Framework}

\subsection{Clinical Encounter Simulation}

We simulate complete multi-turn encounters because static QA
benchmarks cannot measure premature action, evidence-grounded
reasoning, or calibration under accumulated uncertainty. Each
encounter runs for up to 10 turns across four components
(Fig.~\ref{fig:arch}).

\textbf{Doctor Agent.} GPT-5 prompted as a clinician. At every turn
it produces three mandatory structured fields alongside free-text
reasoning:

\vspace{2pt}
{\small\texttt{DIAGNOSIS:~<disease~or~``unknown''>}\\
\texttt{CONFIDENCE:~<0.0\,--\,1.0>}\\
\texttt{ACTION:~<from~the~fixed~action~space>}}
\vspace{2pt}

\noindent The action space is: \{\texttt{ask\_question},
\texttt{order\_lab\_test}, \texttt{order\_imaging},
\texttt{prescribe\_medication},
\texttt{prescribe\_high\_risk\_medication},
\texttt{admit\_patient}, \texttt{refer\_specialist},
\texttt{discharge}, \texttt{advise\_followup}\}.
Structured output makes the model's intended physical action
unambiguous at every turn.

\textbf{Patient Agent.} A second GPT-5 instance holding the hidden
clinical profile. Unlike the template-based patient simulator in
AgentClinic~\cite{schmidgall2025agentclinic}, which delivers
pre-scripted JSON responses, our patient agent generates natural
language conditioned on what the doctor actually asked. This enforces
genuine information asymmetry and prevents the trivial strategy of
requesting all available information at once.

\textbf{Measurement Agent.} Handles selective EMR data injection.
It cross-references the doctor's explicit requests against available
test results and examination findings, returning only the requested
data. It tracks per turn how many distinct tests were requested
versus found, producing per-case diagnostic precision scores
unavailable from any prior framework.

\textbf{Encounter protocol.} An encounter terminates early if
confidence $\geq 0.8$ after at least three turns, enforcing minimum
information gathering before commitment. Three consecutive identical
actions trigger a system override. Triage vital signs are provided
at encounter start, reflecting standard clinical practice.

\textbf{Correctness evaluation.}
Diagnostic correctness is evaluated in two stages. First, string
normalisation strips hedging qualifiers (``suspected'',
``probable'', etc.) and checks for substring overlap. If this
fast-pass fails, an LLM judge is invoked with the following prompt:
\emph{``Are these clinically equivalent, or is the prediction an
accurate synonym of the gold standard? Return True only if a
clinician would treat these as the same working diagnosis. Ignore
differences in specificity that do not change the initial management
plan. Return strictly True or False and nothing else.''} We use a
\texttt{startswith(``true'')} check on the lower-cased response to
prevent false positives from phrases such as ``not true''. Cases
such as disc herniation vs.\ lumbar radiculopathy (same initial
management) are marked correct; Hirschsprung disease
vs.\ intussusception (different management and aetiology) are
marked incorrect. This two-stage design limits false positives while
handling clinically accepted synonyms.

\subsection{Dataset}

We use AgentClinic-MedQA~\cite{schmidgall2025agentclinic}, which
converts USMLE-style questions into multi-turn encounters with patient
history, examination findings, test results, and gold-standard
diagnoses. We evaluate 50 cases in a single run, with full
conversation logs saved per case for post-hoc analysis. All results
should be treated as preliminary indicators ahead of the planned
full 200-case evaluation.

\subsection{Safety Metrics}

\textbf{Physical harm scores.} Each action is assigned a harm score
on a 0--4 ordinal scale reflecting the risk of patient harm if the
action is taken based on an incorrect diagnosis (Table~\ref{tab:harm}).
The scale is novel but grounded in established clinical safety
principles. Scores correspond to the severity tiers used in adverse
event reporting frameworks such as the AHRQ Common Formats and the
NCC MERP Medication Error Index~\cite{nccmerp2001,ahrq2019}: no harm
(0), near-miss or minimal harm (1), moderate harm (2), serious harm
(3), and life-threatening harm (4). \texttt{discharge} and
\texttt{prescribe\_high\_risk\_medication} score 4 because sending an
undiagnosed seriously ill patient home, or administering chemotherapy
or anticoagulants on an incorrect indication, are recognised
life-threatening errors in clinical governance
literature~\cite{balogh2015improving}. We acknowledge these scores
are ordinal and expert-assigned; validation against clinician surveys
or adverse event databases is a priority for future work.

