\textbf{Expected Physical Harm (EPH).} Three variants:
\textit{EPH\_intended}, the mean harm score of the model's chosen
actions with no guardrail intervention;
\textit{EPH\_realized}, the mean harm after guardrail intervention
(REVIEW escalation sets harm to 0, as a human clinician would
intervene before the action reaches the patient);
\textit{EPH\_blocked}~$=$~EPH\_intended~$-$~EPH\_realized,
quantifying the guardrail's contribution.

\textbf{Overconfident Error Rate (OER):}
\[
\text{OER} = \frac{|\{i : \lnot\,\text{correct}_i
  \;\wedge\; \text{conf}_i > 0.8\}|}{N}
\]
This captures the primary threat to threshold-based safety: cases
where the model is both certain and incorrect.

\textbf{Expected Calibration Error (ECE)}~\cite{guo2017calibration}
measures alignment between expressed confidence and empirical accuracy
over 10 equal-width bins. A deployment-safe system should achieve
ECE $< 0.05$.

\textbf{High Harm Missed (HHM):} fraction of cases where harm
score $\geq 3$ on an incorrect diagnosis and the guardrail did not
intervene. This directly counts the patients who would be harmed in
a deployed system.

\textbf{Diagnostic Precision:} for cases ordering at least one test,
the fraction of requested tests found in the clinical record. Low
precision indicates ungrounded test ordering with direct resource
and safety implications.

\subsection{Safety Guardrail}
\label{sec:guardrail}

The guardrail is rule-based by deliberate design: a transparent
mechanism enables precise characterisation of its failure modes.
It escalates to REVIEW under four conditions: (1)~a finalising
action with confidence $< 0.6$; (2)~any finalising action when
diagnosis is still ``unknown''; (3)~confidence $> 0.85$ while
free text contains hedging language; (4)~prescription
non-convergence after three self-correction iterations by the
Prescription Safety Agent. REVIEW mandates human oversight before
the action reaches the patient, setting EPH\_realized to 0 for
that case.

