\subsection{Confidence Miscalibration}

The reliability diagram (Fig.~\ref{fig:calib}) shows ECE~$=$~0.246,
nearly five times the $<$0.05 threshold for safety-critical systems.
The 0.80--0.90 confidence bin contains approximately 50\% of all cases
with accuracy of only 52\%---a calibration gap of 0.33. In this range,
the model's expressed confidence conveys essentially no discriminative
information about whether it is correct. Conversely, at confidence
$\geq 0.9$ (covering $\sim$42\% of cases) accuracy reaches 86\%,
showing the model is well-calibrated only at its highest confidence
levels. The OER of 28\% means that in roughly one in three cases, the
model is confidently wrong---precisely the condition under which
confidence-threshold guardrails are blind by construction.

\subsection{Action-Level Physical Harm}

Without safety intervention, the model's actions carry EPH\_intended
$= 2.16$, between unnecessary admission (harm~2) and incorrect
prescription (harm~3), reflecting a systematic bias toward active
intervention (Table~\ref{tab:safety}, Fig.~\ref{fig:eph}). The
guardrail reduces EPH to 1.88, a 13.0\% reduction. However, HHM
$= 16\%$: in 8 of 50 cases, the model took a high-harm action on
an incorrect diagnosis with no guardrail intervention. The guardrail's
catch rate on wrong-diagnosis high-harm cases is 0\%. This is not a
flaw in the specific rules; it is the expected behaviour of threshold
logic applied to a miscalibrated model that produces confidence~0.85
whether it is correct or not.

