\section{Discussion}

\subsection{The Structural Failure of Threshold-Based Safety}

The guardrail's 0\% catch rate on wrong-diagnosis high-harm cases is
the expected behaviour of correctly implemented threshold logic applied
to a miscalibrated model. In the 0.80--0.90 confidence band, covering
the majority of cases, the model produces the same confidence score
whether it is correct or incorrect. No threshold value can
discriminate these outcomes. This analysis generalises: any physically
situated AI agent that is systematically miscalibrated will defeat
threshold-based safety shields, because the signal the shield monitors
carries no discriminative information in the range that matters. The
clinical domain makes this visible because ground truth is available.
In robotics or autonomous vehicles, the same failure mode may be
present and harder to characterise.

\subsection{Paths Toward Safer Architectures}

Three directions follow from the failure taxonomy.
\emph{Post-hoc calibration}~\cite{guo2017calibration}: applying
temperature scaling to remap expressed confidence to empirical
accuracy before it enters guardrail logic would lower the effective
threshold for the overconfident 0.85 range, targeting
Type~C (high-harm miss) cases without retraining.
\emph{Evidence-grounded action verification}: checking whether the
chosen action is consistent with the evidence gathered during the
encounter---detectable without knowing the true diagnosis, and
targeted at the over-ordering problem.
\emph{Dual-agent verification}: a second independent agent evaluating
the case from scratch and flagging disagreement, replicating the
clinical second-opinion protocol without requiring ground truth.

\subsection{Leveraging Conversation Logs}

Full conversation logs are available for all 50 cases. These enable
three analyses beyond aggregate metrics: (1)~per-case confidence
trajectory plots, revealing whether confidence rises with evidence
or anchors early regardless of new findings; (2)~qualitative case
studies for the four high-harm miss cases, tracing the specific
conversational path from symptom presentation to dangerous action;
(3)~test request extraction cross-referenced against available data,
providing qualitative examples of the over-ordering finding beyond
summary statistics. These analyses are ongoing.

\subsection{Nomenclature and Research Lineage}

We distinguish between two entities to avoid confusion. \emph{Med-Guard}
(introduced in~\cite{jain2024medguard}) is the clinical decision
support system: a multi-agent architecture with Doctor, Prescription
Writer, Prescription Safety, and Test Safety agents designed to assist
clinical decision-making. The \emph{Med-Guard Evaluation Framework}
(this paper) repurposes that architecture as a measurement instrument:
it adds the LLM Patient Agent, the Measurement Agent, and the physical
harm metrics to evaluate safety properties of arbitrary LLMs placed
in the Doctor Agent role. The framework is the contribution; Med-Guard
is the architecture on which it is built.

\subsection{Limitations}

Harm scores are ordinal and expert-assigned, pending validation
against clinician surveys. The 50-case evaluation is a preliminary
proof-of-concept; all percentage results should be interpreted
cautiously, as the full 200-case evaluation is in progress.
AgentClinic-MedQA represents structured USMLE presentations that may
be more archetypal than real clinical encounters. The LLM judge for
correctness may introduce systematic errors in clinically adjacent
cases.

% ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Conclusion}

We have presented the first systematic action-level safety evaluation
of a frontier LLM in multi-turn clinical diagnosis. GPT-5 achieves
competitive accuracy (62\%) but is severely miscalibrated
($\text{ECE}=0.246$), exhibits diagnostic over-ordering (precision
0.41, find rate 28\%), and its safety guardrail catches 0\% of
dangerous wrong-diagnosis cases. The core finding is architectural:
confidence-threshold safety is structurally inadequate against
overconfident wrong decisions, the failure mode that matters most for
patient safety. Clinical AI systems are physically situated agents.
They deserve to be evaluated, and safeguarded, with the same rigour
that the physical AI safety community has brought to robots and
autonomous vehicles.

